There's no auth-service source code in this workspace — just knowledge files. I can see from the architecture docs that auth-service is Kotlin, uses gRPC internally, and runs on EKS.

Since the load balancer (ALB) needs the health check, you'll want a simple HTTP endpoint — ALBs don't natively probe gRPC. Here's what to add:

**Option 1: If using Ktor** (lightweight, fits the "minimal dependencies" preference):

```kotlin
// In your Application.kt or a new HealthRoutes.kt
fun Application.configureHealthCheck() {
    routing {
        get("/health") {
            call.respond(HttpStatusCode.OK, mapOf("status" to "UP"))
        }
    }
}
```

**Option 2: If using Spring Boot:**

```kotlin
// HealthController.kt
@RestController
class HealthController {
    @GetMapping("/health")
    fun health(): ResponseEntity<Map<String, String>> {
        return ResponseEntity.ok(mapOf("status" to "UP"))
    }
}
```

Spring Boot also has Actuator (`/actuator/health`) built-in if you add `spring-boot-starter-actuator`, but that pulls in more dependencies.

**Option 3: gRPC Health Checking Protocol** (if using an NLB/gRPC-aware LB instead):

```kotlin
// Register the standard gRPC health service
server = ServerBuilder.forPort(port)
    .addService(yourAuthService)
    .addService(HealthStatusManager().healthService)
    .build()
```

For the ALB target group config, point the health check at `GET /health` with a 200 expected response.

